CI check script (bash) that enforces every real member crate's `Cargo.toml` opts into the workspace lint table; run standalone or as part of the lint-gate pipeline alongside `no_allow_check.sh`.

Domain fact: the workspace root's `[workspace.lints]` (defined in the top-level `Cargo.toml`, see `docs/SPEC.md` Compiler section) only takes effect for a member crate if that crate's own manifest contains a `[lints]` table with `workspace = true`. This script fails CI for any crate manifest that omits that opt-in, since such a crate would otherwise silently build with none of the restriction lints enforced.

Mechanics worth knowing if editing: takes an optional root dir as `$1` (default `.`), `cd`s into it, and requires it be a git work tree (`git rev-parse --is-inside-work-tree`) or exits 1 immediately. Manifest discovery is via `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard -- 'Cargo.toml' '*/Cargo.toml'`, NUL-delimited into `mapfile`, not a filesystem walk — mirrors the same rationale documented in `no_allow_check.sh` (avoids racing a concurrent `target/` writer and keeps output a pure function of tracked/untracked-but-not-ignored repo state, not build artifacts). A manifest is skipped entirely if it lacks a `[package]` table — that's the heuristic for "this is the virtual workspace root, not a real crate," consistent with sibling scripts in this directory.

The actual check is an `awk` state machine, not a simple grep: it sets `in_lints=1` only upon seeing a line matching `^\[lints\]`, clears it on any other `^\[` (e.g. `[dependencies]`, `[workspace]`), and only counts a `workspace = true` line as satisfying the requirement if seen while `in_lints` is set — this deliberately avoids false-passing on a `workspace = true` that appears under `[workspace]` or some other table instead of `[lints]`. Exits 1 (`FAIL`) accumulating across all offending manifests rather than stopping at the first, and prints one `FAIL: <path> missing ...` line per bad manifest to stderr.

Invariant: never inspects manifests outside git's tracked/untracked-but-not-ignored view, and never treats a non-package manifest (no `[package]` table) as an error regardless of its `[lints]` content. Comment in the script explicitly notes this check is a manifest-level property and is not expected to be superseded by the (mentioned but not implemented here) dylint pipeline.